Question

An isosceles trapezoid is the region between the following curves:

\[z ~=~ 0.9x\] \[z ~=~ -0.9x\] \[x ~=~ 2.91\] \[x ~=~ 9.76\]


That trapezoid is revolved around the \(z\) axis to produce a toroid. A wireframe animation of the toroid is shown below.


Find the volume of the toroid using shell integration. The tolerance is \(\pm 1\) cubic unit.

Solution

To use shell integration, we split the volume into a bunch of cylindrical shells.


Each shell has a radius, height, and an infinitesimal thickness.


The infinitesimal volume can be found as the difference of two cylinders’ volumes.

\[dV ~=~ \pi(r+dr)^2h-\pi r^2h\]

We apply binomial theorem.

\[dV ~=~ \pi r^2 h + 2\pi r h\,dr + \pi h \, (dr)^2-\pi r^2h\]

Notice two terms eliminate because they are opposites.

\[dV ~=~ 2\pi r h\,dr + \pi h \, (dr)^2\]

Remember, \(dr\) is an infinitesimal amount (\(dr\) is near 0), so the second term can be ignored.

\[dV ~=~ 2\pi r h\,dr\]

We need to get height as a function of \(r\). We can get this from the two lines.

\[h = 0.9 r - (-0.9) r\]

\[h = 1.8 r\]
